SIMPLE: fang
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fang
<hw>Fang</hw> <pr>(f⟦acr⟧ng)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>fangen</ets>, <ets>fongen</ets>, <ets>fon</ets> (<it>g</it> orig.
only in p. p. and imp. tense), AS. <ets>f⟦omac⟧n</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>vangen</ets>, OHG. <ets>f⟦amac⟧han</ets>, G. <ets>fahen</ets>,
<ets>fangen</ets>, Icel. <ets>f⟦amac⟧</ets>, Sw. <ets>f⟦aring⟧</ets>,
<ets>f⟦aring⟧nga</ets>, Dan. <ets>fange</ets>, <ets>faae</ets>, Goth.
<ets>fahan</ets>, and prob. to E. <ets>fair</ets>, <ets>peace</ets>,
<ets>pact</ets>. Cf. <er>Fair</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To catch; to seize, as with the teeth; to lay hold of; to gripe; to
clutch.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He's in the law's clutches; you see he's <qex>fanged</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>J. Webster.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To enable to catch or tear; to furnish with
fangs.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Chariots <xex>fanged</xex> with scythes.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Philips.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fang</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fang
<hw>Fang</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Fang</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>;
cf. AS. <ets>fang</ets> a taking, booty, G. <ets>fang</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The tusk of an animal, by which the
prey is seized and held or torn; a long pointed tooth; esp., one of the
usually erectile, venomous teeth of serpents. Also, one of the falcers
of a spider.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Since I am a dog, beware my <qex>fangs</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any shoot or other thing by which hold is
taken.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The protuberant <qex>fangs</qex> of the yucca.</q>
<rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The root, or one of the branches
of the root, of a tooth. See <er>Tooth</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A niche in the side of an adit
or shaft, for an air course.</def> <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>A projecting tooth or prong, as
in a part of a lock, or the plate of a belt clamp, or the end of a tool,
as a chisel, where it enters the handle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The valve of a pump
box.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A bend or loop of a rope.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>In a fang</b></col>, <cd>fast entangled.</cd> --
<col><b>To lose the fang</b></col>, <cd>said of a pump when the water
has gone out</cd>; hence: <col><b>To fang a pump</b></col>, <cd>to
supply it with the water necessary to make it operate.</cd>
<mark>[Scot.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fanged</ent>⟦br⟧
